Tembisa Hospital has been indentified as one of three hospitals equipped with measures to treat victims of a possible outbreak of the coronavirus, if it were to make its way to South Africa. This is the same hospital at the centre of a backlash just last week after 10 babies died in its neonatal ward between November and December last year due to a carbapenem-resistant enterobacteriaceae (CRE) outbreak. Carbapenems are a class of highly effective antibiotics, usually used to treat severe or high-risk bacterial infections, and are usually reserved as a last line of defence for multidrug-resistant bacterial infections. ALSO...